{%- comment -%}
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
WAITLIST FORM (custom vcollect)
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Replaces the buy buttons in two situations:
  - "coming_soon": the release date is still in the future, the product was never on sale
  - "restock": every variant is out of stock, the product was on sale and will come back

Both cases collect the same thing, an email tied to the product, so they share one form. Only the wording changes:
telling a shopper "don't miss the release" on a product they already know is sold out reads as a mistake.

Uses the native {% form 'customer' %} tag rather than a third-party app: it creates the customer with marketing consent
and applies a per-product tag, so the launch email is a Shopify Email campaign sent to a segment on that tag. Signups
are unlimited and the first 10 000 emails per month are free, where the free tiers of back-in-stock apps cap out at
10 to 50 alerts per month.

********************************************
Why a plain native submission
********************************************

The shop sits behind bot protection (a Cloudflare managed challenge plus Shopify's own hCaptcha on customer forms).
That protection is built around a normal full-page form submission: the challenge page runs, sets its clearance
cookie and lets the POST through, exactly as it already does for the same form on the product page. Every attempt to
avoid the reload with fetch or a hidden iframe fought that protection and failed (three dead ends on 23/07/2026), so
this form submits natively, like the product page that works.

A collection page only adds two wrinkles, both handled in assets/custom-waitlist.js:
  - return_to brings the shopper back to the very collection they left, not to /contact, and carries
    waitlist_posted=<product id> so the script knows which drawer to reopen with its confirmation;
  - there is deliberately NO form.posted_successfully? branch here: Shopify raises that flag for EVERY customer form
    on the page after any post, which would light up a confirmation in drawers nobody submitted. The confirmation is
    shown client-side, only in the one drawer whose id matches waitlist_posted.

Without JavaScript the form still records the email natively; only the on-screen confirmation needs the script.

********************************************
Supported variables
********************************************

* product: the product the visitor is queuing for
* mode: "coming_soon" (default) or "restock"
* form_id: an optional explicit form ID
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- liquid
  assign waitlist_form_id = form_id
  if waitlist_form_id == blank
    assign waitlist_form_id = 'waitlist-form-' | append: product.id | append: '-' | append: section.id
  endif

  assign waitlist_mode = mode | default: 'coming_soon'

  assign release_date = product.metafields.vcollect.date_sortie.value
  assign release_date_formatted = release_date | date: '%d/%m/%Y'

  comment
    One tag per product, whatever the mode: a shopper who queued before the release and one who queued after a
    stockout both want the same email. Splitting them would mean two segments to merge before every campaign.
  endcomment
  assign waitlist_tag = 'liste-attente-' | append: product.handle

  if waitlist_mode == 'restock'
    assign intro_text = 'product.waitlist.intro_restock' | t
    assign submit_label = 'product.waitlist.submit_restock' | t
    assign success_text = 'product.waitlist.success_restock' | t
  else
    assign intro_text = 'product.waitlist.intro' | t
    assign submit_label = 'product.waitlist.submit' | t
    assign success_text = 'product.waitlist.success' | t
  endif

  comment
    Server-side default landing URL. The script overwrites it on submit with the full current URL (filters included),
    but a no-JS submission still returns to this collection instead of /contact.
  endcomment
  assign return_to = request.path | append: '?waitlist_posted=' | append: product.id
-%}

<waitlist-signup class="waitlist v-stack gap-4" data-product-id="{{ product.id }}">
  {%- comment -%} The release date only means something before the launch. {%- endcomment -%}
  {%- if release_date != blank and waitlist_mode != 'restock' -%}
    <p class="text-sm text-subdued">
      {{- 'product.waitlist.release_date' | t: date: release_date_formatted -}}
    </p>
  {%- endif -%}

  {%- form 'customer', id: waitlist_form_id, return_to: return_to, class: 'waitlist__form v-stack gap-3' -%}
    <input type="hidden" name="contact[tags]" value="{{ waitlist_tag | escape }}">

    <div class="waitlist__fields v-stack gap-3" data-waitlist-fields>
      <p class="text-sm">{{ intro_text }}</p>

      {%- liquid
        assign email_label = 'product.waitlist.email_label' | t
        render 'input', type: 'email', label: email_label, name: 'contact[email]', value: form.email, required: true

        render 'button', content: submit_label, type: 'submit', size: 'xl'
      -%}
    </div>

    {%- comment -%}
    role="status" makes screen readers announce the confirmation the script reveals on the shopper's return.
    {%- endcomment -%}
    <div role="status">
      <p class="waitlist__success text-sm" data-waitlist-success hidden>{{ success_text }}</p>
    </div>
  {%- endform -%}
</waitlist-signup>
